Description: The GNOME virtual file-system libraries
DescDetail: <<
GNOME VFS is the GNOME virtual file system. It is the foundation of the
Nautilus file manager. It provides a modular architecture and ships with
several modules that implement support for file systems, http, ftp and others.
It provides a URI-based API, a backend supporting asynchronous file operations,
a MIME type manipulation library and other features.
<<
DescPackaging: <<
  Although this package has a GPL/LGPL license, it is marked Restrictive since
  it links to openssl.

  Remove -lssl and -lcrypto flags from *.la files to make dependent
  programs link to those crypto libraries directly by passing their
  own flags.  (makes %n and %n-ssl more interchangeable at runtime)

  v2.6 had libexecdir as %p/lib/%n so switching to/from -ssl changed
  where the daemon was. Now always put in %p/sbin in both packages,
  where one expects to find daemons, and add symlinks to support
  scripts that still use the old location.

  Lots of functions ignored due to packager inertia. Some of these are
  probably due to previous use of -undefined suppress, which caused
  ./configure tests for presence of functions to succeed even if the
  function did not exist.

  Disable optional support libs that did not exist in previous
  versions, have dependencies that don't exist in fink, have been
  disabled in previous versions of the fink package, or were
  improperly autodetected (missing BuildDepends) in previous versions
  of the fink package.

  Uses included neon lib instead of fink's neon25 package. WONTFIX.
  See: http://bugzilla.gnome.org/show_bug.cgi?id=332290
<<
